I"√-<img src="/assets/rBand/Planed.jpg" alt="Planed">
<div class="image-caption">Shavings!</div>

<p>My wife has a neck injury for which she uses <a href="https://www.amazon.com/resistance-bands-fitness-bands/b?ie=UTF8&amp;node=3407931">resistance bands</a> in her therapy regimen.</p>

<p>The rub is that the bands need to be held at certain positions, in various ways, so that she can pull on them. Our house is basically a labyrinth of workshops, we don‚Äôt even have a living room. We‚Äôre both artsy/crafty folk that don‚Äôt have much of an interest in a ‚Äúnormal‚Äù house. The result is that there‚Äôs only one place in the house where she can spread her arms out.</p>

<p>That place also happens to be the main walkway in the house. Which means I don‚Äôt want things on the wall where I‚Äôll inevitably run in to them and destroy it, or me.</p>

<p>My solution was to build a portable resistance band holding station that can be clamped on the wall.</p>

<p>Luckily, this also buys me some time for my next review that‚Äôs coming up later this week. It‚Äôs taking me some extra time so consider this post my ninja-kung-fu redirection while I finish it.</p>

<p>On with it!</p>

<!--more-->

<p><strong>If you have any questions or comments, please comment below! I read every comment and respond to most.</strong> No registration is necessary to comment, so don‚Äôt be shy.</p>

