<h1 id="wood">Wood</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Wood.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Wood.jpg" alt="Wood">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Wood</div>

<p>I‚Äôm starting with a portion of a pine 2‚Äùx4‚Äù. Simple construction lumber. It‚Äôs worth about $2.</p>

<h1 id="marks">Marks</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Marks.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Marks.jpg" alt="Marks">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Marks</div>

<p>My wife put masking tape marks on the wall where she wants holders to go, but little does she know my plan!</p>

<p>(Spoiler: She didn‚Äôt like my plan, and wanted exactly what she asked for. Ugh.)</p>

<h1 id="crosscut">Crosscut</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Crosscut.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Crosscut.jpg" alt="Crosscut">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Crosscut</div>

<p>I cut the wood to 36‚Äù/0.9m. It‚Äôs cut with <a href="https://www.fine-tools.com/ryoba.html">a Ryoba</a> using the crosscut side.</p>

<h1 id="mark-parallel">Mark Parallel</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/MarkParallel.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/MarkParallel.jpg" alt="MarkParallel">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">MarkParallel</div>

<p>The wood I‚Äôm working with was cut poorly by some dumb bastard (me). So I need to make the sides parallel.</p>

<p>I use a <a href="http://www.leevalley.com/us/wood/page.aspx?p=59455&amp;cat=1,42936,59455">Lee Valley Marking Gauge</a> to mark a line from one side to the other.</p>

<p>I then plane to this line. Since the marking gauge cuts a light score line, you can actually see a telltale thin shaving of wood come off when you hit the mark.</p>

<h1 id="transition">Transition</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Transition.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Transition.jpg" alt="Transition">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Transition</div>

<p>On the left you can see the fuzzy low spot. On the right is where the plane is cutting. I take down the high spot until it cuts the low spot as well.</p>

<p>Then I lightly fine tune the cut to match <a href="#mark-parallel">my parallel mark</a>.</p>

<h1 id="planed">Planed</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Planed.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Planed.jpg" alt="Planed">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Planed</div>

<p>Done. Planed. 90¬∞ and parallel on all sides.</p>

<h1 id="center">Center</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Center.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Center.jpg" alt="Center">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Center</div>

<p>To find the center of the board I create a mark that‚Äôs 90¬∞ to a face. I have to do this because the end of the work is not trued.</p>

<p>I then draw an X with the legs meeting the mark and the edge of the board.</p>

<p>Where these meet is the center.</p>

<h1 id="mark-divisions">Mark Divisions</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/MarkDivisions.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/MarkDivisions.jpg" alt="MarkDivisions">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">MarkDivisions</div>

<p>I mark divisions down the center line every 2‚Äù/5cm.</p>

<h1 id="drill">Drill</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Drill.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Drill.jpg" alt="Drill">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Drill</div>

<p>Now I drill holes at each mark using a 1.25‚Äù/3cm <a href="http://www.rockler.com/how-to/the-value-of-forstner-bits/">forstner bit</a>. This is a lot of work!</p>

<h1 id="drilled">Drilled</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Drilled.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Drilled.jpg" alt="Drilled">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Drilled</div>

<p>Really‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs a lot of work. I removed about 40% of the wood with the drill bit. Don‚Äôt let it get hot, and clear the chips frequently.</p>

<p>Treat your drill bits well and they will treat you well.</p>

<h1 id="clean">Clean</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Clean.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Clean.jpg" alt="Clean">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Clean</div>

<p>The side that the bit pushes into is very clean‚Ä¶</p>

<h1 id="dirty">Dirty</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Dirty.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Dirty.jpg" alt="Dirty">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Dirty</div>

<p>Even with a support board behind it, the exit side is nasty.</p>

<h1 id="cleaning">Cleaning</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Cleaning.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Cleaning.jpg" alt="Cleaning">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Cleaning</div>

<p>I clean up the exit holes by planing the wood down past the chipped sections. It takes about 10 passes with a heavy set, sharp plane.</p>

<h1 id="cleaned">Cleaned</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Cleaned.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Cleaned.jpg" alt="Cleaned">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Cleaned</div>

<p>That‚Äôs the dirty side‚Ä¶ nice and clean.</p>

<h1 id="roundover">Roundover</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Roundover.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Roundover.jpg" alt="Roundover">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Roundover</div>

<p>Now I want to make it pleasant to hold. I use a 1/2‚Äù/1.25cm roundover bit and roundover <em>everything</em></p>

<h1 id="rounded-over">Rounded Over</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/RoundedOver.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/RoundedOver.jpg" alt="RoundedOver">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">RoundedOver</div>

<p>This is the result. You can see that where the bit engages the endgrain there‚Äôs some burning. I remove that with sandpaper. There‚Äôs really not any way around this except having a very sharp router bit, and let the bit cool occasionally.</p>

<p>Of course I was impatient and rather than let the bit cool occasionally, I ‚Äúsaved time‚Äù by zipping through it‚Ä¶ then spending 30 minutes sanding.</p>

<p>Save 5 minutes, spend 30. That‚Äôs how I do it. D‚Äôoh :(</p>

<h1 id="cut-open">Cut Open</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/CutOpen.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/CutOpen.jpg" alt="CutOpen">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">CutOpen</div>

<p>Every other hole is cut open. Some places need to have the band threaded through, and those will stay closed.</p>

<p>Some sections need to have the band hooked in to the rack. Cutting the hole open near the top/bottom of it lets this take place.</p>

<p>The opening is about 1/4‚Äù/6mm. One side is tangent to the inner circle.</p>

<p>If you are making one of these, make sure you cut open the appropriate side. Take in to account which direction the band will be pulled so that you don‚Äôt have the band slipping out!</p>

<p>There‚Äôs another way to create this entry location that is vector agnostic, but this is just a prototype.</p>

<h1 id="file">File</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/File.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/File.jpg" alt="File">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">File</div>

<p>I use fine cut <a href="https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&amp;rls=en&amp;q=iwasaki+file&amp;ie=UTF-8&amp;oe=UTF-8">iwasaki file</a> to make things look nice.</p>

<h1 id="finished">Finished</h1>

<a href="/assets/rBand/Finished.jpg">
<img src="/assets/rBand/Thumbnails/Finished.jpg" alt="Finished">
</a>
<div class="image-caption">Finished</div>

<p>That‚Äôs it! Here it is in use by my wife. It clamps to the wall near the kitchen. She can then do her exercises and take it down so I don‚Äôt destroy my face on it as I walk by.</p>

<p>It turns out that she doesn‚Äôt like it <em>that much</em>. The holes don‚Äôt line up exactly where she needs them‚Ä¶ by a few millimeters. The pine isn‚Äôt as strong as we‚Äôd like, which I expected.</p>

<p>I‚Äôll have to build another one, but since this was just a prototype that‚Äôs fine. I‚Äôll make another one in a while.</p>

<p>p.s. Those resistance band handles I made ;) They‚Äôre pretty neato.</p>

<p>p.p.s. No, we do not have cabinet doors in our kitchen. I don‚Äôt like them.</p>

